We put an ‘MY’ freeze brand on the left shoulder of all of our horses that indicates ownership/who bred them. But we also put a number on the left buttock (alongside the tail) of each horse. This number is based on the year they were born. All our foals born in 2016 have a 6 butt brand. All our foals born in 2022 have a 2 butt brand, etc. We started this a few years back and it has been a very fast and convenient way to always know their age. 

On rare occasion we will have someone contact us that purchased a horse with our brand from another party and there were no papers and little history with them. That butt brand helps us to ID the horse and give the portion of history, pedigree, training, etc that we can provide. 

Freeze branding is a method using liquid nitrogen that causes the hair to grow in white for permanent identification. We also use freeze branding on our angus cattle as a permanent identification in the case that tags can fall out and can fade etc.

The 1971 stallion, Oklahoma Fuel, was advertised as a “proven source for speed” way back in 1998 and we’ve found that still true today. He is one of only a few horses to ever run AAA at all seven official AQHA distances with a Speed Index of 108. He passed his incredible speed and athleticism onto his progeny. Oklahoma Fuel sired 21 foal crops with 201 race starters, 94 winners, 3 stakes winners, 4 superior race awards, 98 ROMs, 80 2yr old ROMs. 

Oklahoma Fuel is the sire to Charles Pogue's Oklahoma Top Hat horse (aka "Scooter”), who won the PRCA head horse of the year title not just once or twice but six times. 

He’s also the sire to Louisiana Fuel and Okla Breeze Bar (aka “Texas”) who we have been crossing on our Driftwood bred mares. There are 16 head of 3, 4, and 5-year-old geldings in our June sale that are sired by these own sons of Oklahoma Fuel.

He scores, runs hard, and handles cattle so well with his powerful athletic move. General has a huge motor and is very trainable and athletic. He has continued to progress and win in the arena as well as the pasture. ⁣
⁣
His first set of geldings sold in our 2021 sale and averaged over $18k each. His colts are good-looking, balanced, and have the same kind of class that makes General a favorite.⁣
⁣
General’s paternal half sister was the buckskin mare that @derrickbegay roped on at the NFR in 2021. This line of horses has got what it takes. ⁣
⁣
We rode two crops of colts out of General’s sire, Ninja Wood, and have been very pleased with them but we, unfortunately, lost him. His colts had speed, athleticism, and natural ability. General’s grandsire is Wilywood, a phenomenal rope and ranch horse sire with unbeatable dispositions. General’s dam is a proven producer and sired by the great White Lightning Ike.⁣

There are 9 geldings sired by General that we will be selling in our production sale on Saturday, June 24th!

He was just a few points away from qualifying on​ ​the head end, but he had to get back and sire some foals. He was shown in heading, heeling, halter,​ ​reining, sorting, and barrel racing. He acquired 53.5 AQHA points and 6 ABHA points.⁣

From the time General was born, we knew that he was something special. He kept our hopes up when as a two-year-old, he broke out and rode like a dream. General’s grandsire is Wilywood, a phenomenal rope and ranch horse sire with unbeatable dispositions. General’s dam is a proven producer and sired by the great White Lightning Ike.

Our stallions get the spotlight a lot but if we are being honest, the mares are the real MVP’s of our program. Genetically speaking, a foal is 50% its sire and 50% its dam but the dam puts in a lot more than 50% of the work. They are pregnant for 11 months and then birth and feed the foals for another 5. ⁣
⁣
Our broodmares are a compilation of exceptional bloodlines that we have gathered from all across the country over the years and they have proven themselves as top producers. We keep a handful of fillies each year as replacement mares and we make a point to start and ride them so we know exactly what we are putting back into our program. ⁣

“Back in 2017, our twin daughters, Ashley and Morgan, wanted to buy horses of their own while they were still in high school. They’d grown up riding our horses, as I’d instilled a love of horses since before they could walk as babies. They found Memory Ranches online, back when the ranch was still located in New Plymouth, Idaho.⁣
⁣
So we drove up to meet with Monty and he showed us around the ranch. Morgan found her MY horse in a group of four yearling fillies. ‘Haven’, aka MY Snip of Chiffon, is a 2016 mare out of LMP Chiffon Drifter (by Gents Traveler), was curious, bold, and approached the truck. She’s an absolutely beautiful bay with lots of chrome, and has been excellent to work with and train. She’s built like a tank, and steady as a rock.⁣
 ⁣
‘Remmy/Remington’, aka MY Dashing Angel, is a 2017 mare by Indigo James, and has War Concho as a great-grandsire on her dam’s side. She was the dark chocolate brown filly Ashley chose out of the milling herd of weanlings. To this day, Remmy will still lie down with her head in our daughter’s lap. She’s grown into a beautiful, tall, and athletic mare. Remmy is fast like her sire, and has been wonderful to work with.⁣
⁣
Haven and Remmy are phenomenal horses, and are prime examples of the top quality horses bred by Memory Ranches. We love them so much, we set our hearts on owning another horse from Memory Ranches. My husband and I just bought a gelding from the 2023 gelding sale, and have added ‘Stetson’ (He’s a great-grandson of Driftwood Stetson on his dam’s side. His name for the sale was Jonah.) to our happy family.⁣
⁣
If you’re looking for a top quality Quarter Horses for performance, ranch, or trail/pleasure riding, Memory Ranches is the place to go. The Pearce family have an excellent breeding program and some of the best Quarter Horse bloodlines around. I highly recommend Memory Ranches to anyone in need of a great horse.”⁣
⁣
BJ & Tony Wheeler⁣
